		<small><a href="http://www.gamesurge.net/" title="http://www.gamesurge.net/" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64176669"><p><div class="quote"><p>Most cars have a 120VAC outlet somewhere that can provide some power.</p></div><p>Do they?  I drive a 2018 Acura MDX, and my wife drives a 2022 Honda Accord, both hybrids.  Neither has a 120VAC outlet (some MDXes do).  Based on a quick web search, the cars that have outlets are (a) mostly pickups and minivans and (b) often rated for 100W or 150W max supply.  You'll be waiting a long time to charge an EV for even a few miles of travel at 150W.  Some pickup trucks have heavy-duty outlets (up to 2400W), but they're the exception.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64176669">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64176669" class="btn link" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23199469&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64176669" onclick="D2.replyTo(64176669); return false;">Reply to This</a> <span class="ind"></span><a class="btn link" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23199469&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;cid=64176087" onclick="return D2.selectParent(64176087)">Parent</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
