<div id="comment_64176775" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64176775" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64176775" name="comment_link_64176775" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23199469&amp;cid=64176775" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64176775)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64176775" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64176775); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~AmiMoJo">AmiMoJo</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~AmiMoJo">( 196126 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64176775"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64176775"><p>EVs have a 12V battery that runs, among other things, the drivetrain control system. That 12V battery is similar to the one in an ICE, but smaller as it doesn't have to crank an engine.</p><p>In very cold weather it can suffer from more rapid discharge and low voltage, preventing the car from being turned on. Newer EVs do a better job at keeping it topped up, e.g. charging voltage needs to be higher in cold temperatures.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64176775">

</div>
</div>

