			<h4><a id="comment_link_64176875" name="comment_link_64176875" href="//hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23199469&amp;cid=64176875" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64176875)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64176875" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64176875); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~radarskiy">radarskiy</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~radarskiy">( 2874255 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64176875"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64176875"><p>'How do you "start" an EV?'</p><p>An electric motor does not idle. When you intentionally want the motor to not rotate it draws no power. However, there is a failure mode when you apply power but it stalls instead of rotating due to insufficient torque for the load. This is a "failure to start" for an electric motor.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64176875">

</div>
